LHC Data Analysis

Alexander Scheibe

When analyzing our LHC data, we found a ratio of 20 electrons to 18 muons from the e, neutrino and muon, neutrino events. This analysis was adequate because the ratio of electron to muon events was supposed to be about 50/50. Continuing for the ratio of W+/W- we examined 35 W+ and 20 W- events. This analysis is about right because there are supposed to be a few more positive events when compared to negative. Furthermore, when constructing our histogram for 2-lepton events, we examined a peak at around 90 GeV which would indicate Z Boson particles. Along with that, there were also two other peaks at around 3 GeV and 10 GeV. At 3 GeV, this would indicate a J/, while the 10GeV peak would indicate an upsilon particle. For our 4-lepton events, the decays ended up with 2 Z Bosons. These could have come from the Higgs, or other processes. For possible Higg candidates, we found 9 candidates, but only 3 of the events had a mass around 125 GeV which is the Higgs mass. With that, there were two 2 electron/2 muon decays that had a mass of 96.12 GeV and 148.72 GeV. Along with that, there was a 4-electron decay that had a mass of 154.95 GeV. In all, with our data we were able to find three Higg candidates below there is a screenshot of one of the Higg candidate events that we ran into.
